[2026-05-19]
##  Day 20: Adversity Lab – Simulated Crash & Journal Forensics (chronyd_gate hardening)

### Infrastructure Updated
- Enhanced `chronyd_gate.sh` with `healthcheck()` helper function to remove duplicate code and improve maintainability.
- Added `timedatectl makestep` as the primary escalation step for large clock drift / maxjitter scenarios caused by laptop network disconnects (the exact real-world failure this gate was built to solve).
- Implemented proper post-remediation verification with `sleep 10` before declaring RESTORED or FAILED.
- Added `| tee /dev/console` routing (and `StandardOutput=journal+console` in the service unit) in multiple attempts to surface alert banners to the interactive terminal.

### Operations Performed
- Deliberately induced large time drift with `sudo timedatectl set-ntp false` to simulate laptop going offline for an extended period.
- Monitored and correlated logs between `-u chronyd_gate.service` and `-u chronyd` to confirm the gate correctly detected the disabled NTP state, forced `makestep` + restart + enable + `set-ntp true`, and successfully restored synchronization (chronyd selected sources, set TAI offset, and locked frequency).
- Verified three-location workflow: edited in `~/Projects/bin/`, copied to `/usr/local/bin/`, ran `restorecon`, `daemon-reload`, and restarted the timer.
- Confirmed self-healing works end-to-end even when chronyd refused to step time due to excessive jitter/root distance.

### Bugs Resolved
- Rapid "Deactivated successfully" cycling when chronyd could not sync after large drift.
- Duplicate health-check logic (now cleanly wrapped in reusable helper).
- Inconsistent recovery on maxjitter / root-distance errors after network reconnect.
- Alert banners **are** reliably produced and visible in `journalctl -u chronyd_gate.service`, but are **not** appearing in the interactive terminal session when the timer runs the oneshot service (multiple fixes attempted — `tee /dev/console`, `StandardOutput=journal+console`, `exec > >(tee ...)` — still not surfacing; deprioritized for today).

### Repository / Operational Notes
- Gate remains completely silent on healthy runs and only outputs the full `CHRONYD GATE ALERT` / status / `RESTARTING` / `RESTORED` banners on failure.
- Alert output is confirmed present in the journal (as requested), but console visibility when running under the timer remains unresolved for now.
- Pattern is now proven for the specific laptop-disconnect → massive jitter → self-healing use case that has plagued the system for weeks.
- GitHub updated first per new workflow.
- Weak Concepts from prior days (journalctl source filtering `-u chronyd` vs `-u chronyd_gate.service`, `makestep` vs `set-ntp true`, helper function reuse, oneshot timer output behavior) were directly applied under pressure.

[2026-05-17]
##  Day 19: Logic Gate II – Self-Healing Monitors (sshd_gate + chronyd_gate)

### Infrastructure Deployed
- `sshd_gate.sh` — one-shot self-healing monitor for sshd.service; checks both `systemctl is-active` and `ss -lpn | grep -q ':22'`; logs structured events to both file and journal via `log_event()` helper; restarts on failure and verifies outcome.
- `chronyd_gate.sh` — silent-when-healthy self-healing monitor for time synchronization; checks NTP status via `timedatectl` + `systemctl is-active chronyd`; only outputs `CHRONYD GATE ALERT` + status on failure, then runs `daemon-reload`, `restart chronyd`, `timedatectl set-ntp true`, re-checks, and reports RESTORED.
- Matching systemd units: `sshd_gate.service` + `sshd_gate.timer` and `chronyd_gate.service` + `chronyd_gate.timer` (Type=oneshot, OnBootSec=1min, OnUnitActiveSec=60s, RandomizedDelaySec=15s).

### Operations Performed
- Three-location script workflow enforced: edit in `~/Projects/bin/`, production copy in `/usr/local/bin/`, backup in `~/bin.bak/`.
- Deployed timers with `daemon-reload`, `enable --now`, and verified via `journalctl -t sshd_gate` and `journalctl -u chronyd_gate.service`.
- Deliberately broke services (stop/mask, `timedatectl set-ntp false`) to test recovery paths.

### Bugs Resolved

| Error                        | Root Cause                                      | Resolution                                      |
|-----------------------------|-------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------|
| 203/EXEC (Permission denied) | Wrong SELinux context (`user_home_t` on file in /usr/local/bin/) | `restorecon -v` to restore `bin_t` context |
| Rapid service cycling       | `Type=simple` on one-shot script                | Changed to `Type=oneshot` in both .service files |
| Missing '=' syntax error    | Unit file formatting                            | Fixed section headers and directives |
| No alert on timer run       | Remediation outrunning next timer cycle         | Accepted as feature of fast self-healing; manual test confirmed alert works |
| Unit not found              | No `daemon-reload` after creating unit files    | Added mandatory `sudo systemctl daemon-reload` |

### Key Concepts / Distinctions Filed
- `ls -Z` is required on RHEL to see SELinux context (`user_home_t` vs `bin_t`).
- `Type=oneshot` vs `Type=simple` — oneshot for scripts that run once and exit.
- Timer + oneshot service relationship: `[Install]` with `WantedBy=timers.target` belongs on the .timer file.
- Multi-view health checking (systemctl + ss for sshd; timedatectl + systemctl for chronyd).
- Silent-when-healthy + prompt-only-on-failure pattern for low-noise monitoring.
- `restorecon` as the clean way to fix inherited SELinux labels after copying scripts.

### Repository / Operational Notes
- Both gates now live and running via timers.
- Reusable template established for future service monitors.

[2026-05-14]
##  Day 18: find -exec Mass Evacuation Drill

### Infrastructure Deployed
- Built adversarial test environment in `~/playground/` (under sensei home directory, explicitly excluded from Git tracking) containing 40,001 scattered `*.log` files with deep nesting to simulate real-world log accumulation.

### Operations Performed
- Designed and executed a single `find -exec` command with batching `+` terminator to relocate all 40,001 files into a dated archive directory (`~/playground/evilfiles.archive/2026-05-14/`).
- Used `mkdir -p` for idempotent target directory creation.
- Verified success with before/after counts (`find … | wc -l` and `ls … | wc -l`).

### Bugs Resolved
| Error                        | Root Cause                          | Resolution                              |
|-----------------------------|-------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------|
| "missing argument to -exec" | Missing or misplaced terminator     | Added correct `+` batching terminator after `{}` |

### Key Concepts / Distinctions Filed
- `{}` placeholder substitutes each matching filename in `-exec`.
- `+` terminator batches files for fewer command invocations (essential at 40k+ scale); `\\;` runs once per file (correct but inefficient).
- Always quote patterns (`"*.log"`) to prevent shell globbing.
- `mkdir -p` ensures safe, repeatable archive operations.
- Test/lab directories like `playground/` belong outside Git-tracked `Projects/bin/` to avoid committing runtime artifacts.

### Repository / Operational Notes
- `~/playground/` deliberately excluded from Git (not in `~/Projects/bin/` development tree).
- Prepares for Day 22 (`tar` archiving/compression) and production bulk operations.
- Followed updated commit framework (Conventional Commits + structured changelog).

[2026-05-13]
##  Day 17: Service Lab — pulse.sh / pulse.service

### Infrastructure Deployed
- `pulse.sh` — infinite loop; appends timestamp and uptime to log every 30 seconds;
  purpose: generate a heartbeat record for correlating system events with
  clock or connectivity anomalies
- `pulse.service` — systemd unit file managing `pulse.sh`;
  configured for `Type=simple`, `Restart=always`, `WantedBy=multi-user.target`
- Service enabled and confirmed boot-persistent via symlink in
  `/etc/systemd/system/multi-user.target.wants/`

### Bugs Resolved

| Error | Root Cause | Resolution |
|-------|-----------|------------|
| `Unknown section 'UNIT'` | Section headers are title-case in systemd; all-caps silently ignored | Changed to `[Unit]` |
| `Failed to parse service type: Simple` | Directive values require lowercase | Changed to `simple` |
| `Failed to parse restart specifier: Always` | Same case issue | Changed to `always` |
| `203/EXEC` — wrong file | `ExecStart` pointed at log output file, not script | Corrected to `pulse.sh` |
| `203/EXEC` — missing directory | `PULSE_LOG` referenced `/home/sensei/tmp/` which did not exist | Updated path |
| `203/EXEC` — Permission denied | SELinux `init_t` domain cannot execute files in `/tmp` (`user_tmp_t` context) regardless of `chmod` state | Relocated script to `/usr/local/bin/` (`bin_t` context) |
| Log write failure | `PULSE_LOG` used tilde (`~/`) — not expanded by systemd in non-interactive execution context | Replaced with full absolute path |

### Operational Notes
- `daemon-reload` required after every unit file creation or modification —
  without it systemd reads from cached configuration
- `/usr/local/bin/` is the correct location for custom admin scripts on RHEL:
  persistent across reboots, in system `$PATH`, inherits correct SELinux context
- Tilde (`~`) must not be used in any script executed by a non-interactive process
  (systemd, cron, CI/CD pipelines) — use absolute paths only

### Repository Structure
- Production: `/usr/local/bin/pulse.sh` — executed by systemd
- Development: `~/Projects/bin/pulse.sh` — tracked in Git
- Backup: `~/bin.bak/pulse.sh` — local fallback

[2026-05-12]
## Forensic Audit Operations
- Injected synthetic log events via `logger` with explicit priority flags:
  `FORGE_FAILURE` (crit), `SECURITY_BREACH` (alert), `SYSTEM_IDLE` ×2 (info)
- Isolated high-priority entries using `journalctl -t` (syslog identifier)
  rather than piping the full journal to `grep` — avoids loading the
  entire journal into memory on high-volume systems
- Corrected invalid filter attempt: `journalctl -t -n10 26680` fails because
  `-t` expects a string identifier, not a PID; correct syntax is `journalctl _PID=<number>`
- Exported filtered audit results to `day16_audit.json` using `-o json` for
  machine-readable ingestion

### Incident: NTP Desynchronization
- Detected live `chronyd` errors in journal during drill:
  root distance and jitter exceeding configured thresholds on `2.rhel.pool.ntp.org`
- Remediated: restarted and re-enabled `chronyd.service`;
  enabled NTP via `timedatectl set-ntp true`
- Root cause: high-latency upstream pool sources; clock was off by ~116,725 seconds
  before chrony stepped it back into sync

### Key Distinctions Filed
- `journalctl -u` — filter by systemd unit (service-level events)
- `journalctl -t` — filter by syslog identifier (script/app-tagged events)

